\begin{tikzpicture}
  \begin{axis}[
    xmin=-5,xmax=5,
    xlabel={$x$},
    ylabel={$y=f(x)$},
  ]

  \addplot[red, domain=-5:5, thick, samples=100]
    ({x}, {3*x+2});
  \addplot[mark=*, red, fill=white] coordinates {(1,5)};
  \end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}

solution.p:
We decide what type of discontinuity by seeing if we can fix them through canceling common factors. The numerator p(x)=x^3-5x^2+6x can be tested even before factoring. At x=-3, we have p(-3) = -27-5(9)+6(-3) = -90 so that x+3 is not going to be a common factor. There must be a vertical asymptote at x=-3. At x=2, we have p(2) = 8-5(4)+6(2) = 0 so that there will be a common factor that cancels. 
      f(x) &= \frac{x^3-5x^2+6x}{x^2+x-6} 
      &= \frac{x(x^2-5x+6)}{(x+3)(x-2)} 
      &= \frac{x(x-2)(x-3)}{(x+3)(x-2)} 
      &= \frac{x(x-3)}{x+3}, \quad x \ne 2. 
    Because the new formula has an implicit domain involving only x=-3, the discontinuity at x=2 was removable. The graph has a hole at x=2 and a vertical asymptote at x=-3. (Notice the addition of an explicit domain on the last step when we canceled, corresponding  to the hole.)

